  "opinion": "As a woman who's spent most of her life working with hands-on tools and building things in Kansas City, I've seen how science and engineering often feel disconnected from everyday life for people like me. The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers on a chart—it's about who gets to see themselves reflected in the work they do. My parents both only went to primary school, so I never had the same kind of academic exposure to science that many of my peers had. That gap in early education creates a ripple effect, where girls grow up thinking they don't belong in labs or tech fields because they weren't shown it in their own communities. We should address this gap by making science accessible in ways that resonate with people who aren't traditionally 'science people.' For example, integrating hands-on projects into schools that focus on real-world problem-solving, like building sustainable gardens or fixing infrastructure, could help bridge the divide. I've found that when you connect science to things like gardening or woodworking, it becomes something tangible and relevant. The key is to create opportunities where everyone feels they can contribute, not just those who've had years of formal education. If we do this, we'll see more women stepping into science roles not because they're 'better' at it, but because they see themselves in the work they do.",
